A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
The Republicans' leaders justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth, confirming that electoral fraud in the United States is less frequent than the number of people killed by lightning.
The Republicans' lawyers have reported only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for the elections in the various states.
In this sense, the majority of American governments have since 2009 announced new laws that make registration or urination more difficult.
Following the November 2010 elections, this phenomenon gained importance, with 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, declare invalid the right to register as an electoral candidate on the day of the election, and approve the right to vote for which there is a judicial act.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state has requested voters to present a photo identification.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Act in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the last two years, they have promoted draft laws in 34 states that force voters to present a photo identification.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible persons, do not have a photo ID issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a card.
However, there are often more than a hundred dollars to pay to obtain the necessary ID.
Young people, minorities and people with low incomes are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo ID.
That's enough.
The students, who are regarded as voters, who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who choose more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards for elections issued by these associations.
Before 2004, no state had requested proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws calling on voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voices.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, Republican legislators in 2011 have promoted laws in eight states that have abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general elections have contributed to the registration of approximately 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the proportion of newcomers registered in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the time period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they represent only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who had elected in advance.
In contrast, the whites, representing 76% of the voters, made up only 46% of the voters who chose in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The US Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult.
The democratic critics brag about the party political nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the 2012 decisive states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that have passed these laws constitute 171 of the 270 votes required by the Electoral Board to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
