The Higgs Boson Analyzes
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson has aroused some excitement last summer, and this for good reason.
Indeed, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "minimum false" explanation of nature and behavior of matter - but empirically has not yet been observed.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it is really about the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be completely sure about it.
Still, let us assume that this is actually the Higgs, as there seems to be little risk of being deceived, and let us look at what it's all about.
There is an imperative law in this world, which means that two objects cannot be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and try not to be too strong as you will get hurt.
For even if particle physics is a truly strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which means that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantity state", where this "state" is largely composed of some of its characteristics.
From this the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner there are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and who obey Pauli's principle in a manner that is good.
And in the other, the bosons, an evil band of anarchists, who are not holy - certainly not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure, these bosons are divided by the Berkeley laboratories (by the way absolutely amazing) into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it has to be stressed here that these bosons are not all that exotic creatures, as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bottom" of the electromagnetic force.
If a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes its direction, the electromagnetic field is "disrupted" right at this place, in about a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of power".
Stabilising field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" so that this boson shows up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little like a frozen pond, whose surface could only be dismayed by a very large rock.
That's why a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is needed - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself on the fridge.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
For what can all these research be "good", asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to examine all deviations between observations and SM's predictions.
There are, by the way, numerous physicists who hope that such deviations will be found, as the smallest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and block some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great shortcomings, as it does not explain the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (now ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Implication
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be no.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in the Bell laboratories did not assume that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser (the first were pulsated) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was regarded as a "laboratory" at the beginning.
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in the optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor today serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and has presented it with the 2009 Nobel Prize for Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you can never really know it...
