"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he consents to be helped in eating.
Courageously he can even smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is to heal my diarrhoea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeping in his face," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' home.
Returning to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"That depends on the ability of the person", he notes, taking a step backwards.
In the opinion of several people working in palliative care, major events are taking place in the midst of these retrogressions.
The patients assigned to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
You have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they will no longer be burdened with so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who care for them.
For Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and through suffocation".
But through the illness I really met my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't have any more wishes in my life," she says before she accepts that she is put on a mask that helps her breathe.
She still expects a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy in the next few days.
In the home Victor-Gadbois is offered with a group of volunteer body care and help in taking food.
Palliative care is used when there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care on 11.700 inhabitants.
That's very little, considering that one day we'll all die.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Depending on your wishes, you give the deceased a mouth care with Brandy or Pepsi.
Diabetics do not need to control their blood sugar levels anymore.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
In the home Victor-Gadbois is no day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years who enjoys the last family meeting in the yard and is well supported by his pillows while he is in his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two small children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients less than 45 years of age," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the home Victor Gadbois come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the end stage of their life, both at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in the Montreal metropolitan area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
This very great inadequacy in the health care of Quebec ensures that several doctors specialised in palliative care are concerned about the adoption of a law to regulate mortality and assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in order to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has a right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to go to death care.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was 14 days of great pain in the emergency room, without taking measures to relieve them.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of the worst predictions blotted out until the last day.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were minimal when she stopped a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I would stop the treatment, she answered me that she regretted that I was giving up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who have asked to die thank the caregiver for not admitting this wish after their pain has been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, Head of Palliative Care of the Society of Domestic Palliative Care of the Montreal metropolitan area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, the doctors thus often resort to the terminal sedation, which runs out to sleep the patient either sporadicly or permanently until the time of his death.
We cannot continue to do so as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will be increasingly able to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pains are not alleviated all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be eased."
