Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies like the "Credits", which are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is monitored and processed by a central authority each time.
With Bitcoin all network nodes are at the same time keepers of the account book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures the anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction are electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public accounts invoice published throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of temporary central banker, privileged to add this additional line.
It is a fragment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computer "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is right.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other will remain unconnected, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward will be halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be divided into one hundred million pieces, leaving a certain margin...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement of the computing power.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites providing services for Bitcoin were attacked and the bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for payment with real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows this deficiency.
Important actors like Wikipedia refuse to donate this kind of money.
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the invoice book and showed that almost 80% of the Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "Mega closing sale" was launched.
"Three thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, who converted bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are considered in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to get through, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
By the way, the ECB's report provides for a reassessment of the various risks that are considered to be high today in the event of the success of this currency.
