A Constitution With the Breaking Bar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains divided more than ever in relation to the constitutional declaration that temporarily grants it unlimited authority, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To surprise everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of its work.
Egypt has been relying for almost two years on a provisional, severally amended text, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "step right with his feet".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to refrain from their efforts to explain to the Egyptians the text section by section.
For the President, it is also a way of restoring his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest is raging throughout the country.
After affirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote well.
In particular, the Egyptian people are being put to an ultimatum with this recourse to an accelerated vote: "either you vote for my draft or I retain unlimited authority," the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamic members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they believe that they have not been able to bring their views into effect.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to reach the quorum 11 people were added yesterday morning, in a hurry of 11 people, deputy members.
Some are very close to the Moslem brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles have usually been adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the time of prayer, as some members of the body felt that the pendulum of the constitutional assembly was not exactly going.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, finally remains identical with that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is proof of their good will and their respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The Liberals, who only consider this to be a propaganda attack, respond to "shining holiness".
Because according to them, the Islamisation of the Constitution takes place over other articles.
In particular, they have Article 220 in mind, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt's specialist Sophie Pommer, this is disturbing because "the people who are invited to an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
One can see in this the first signs of a theocracy".
The fears of the liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"There is currently no concrete religious commitment to recognize.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, "that there may be a ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are rejected by the religious vocabulary.
One refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question of to what extent civil judges are competent to decide could be raised."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the wide-ranging powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Moslem brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as called for by associations to defend human rights.
The latter also share their fears about the text they regard as a threat to freedom.
Blasphemy will continue to exist, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to free speech, especially for the press.
Furthermore, no longer refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the Head of State will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy places, the navel of the world and a sea of Sole
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and unspoiled nature.
The AIF gives you the five most important reasons for a visit to Israel.
bowing to the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding feast, the walking on the water, the setting of the seastorm and the fishing.
Just here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the shrines, however, are in Jerusalem.
Here believers take the path of suffering or the path of the cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Praetorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the church of the tomb on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where a Christian legend says that the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem is also the most holy place of the Jews - the Lamentations Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 A.D.
Traditionally, people of different denominations leave papers with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Make a trip in the amount
The ruins of the Fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in the year 25 A.D.
They lie on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins with their own strength.
All the others will take an airway to this historic summit.
In the north of the country, between 1600 and 2040 meters high, is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which there are countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an old legend, allegedly pagan gods lived at the summit.
Visit Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all can be visited by just one trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is once the Israel Museum not far from the Parliament.
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls of the Dead Sea, found in rocky caves in the Judean desert, are preserved, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There the collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several rooms of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers at the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are rejected in principle.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most touching section is the monument for children built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and of the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing Something for Health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the banks of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
There are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums in each of the three locations.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea also bathes in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salinity and thus carries even non-swimming on the surface without any problem.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt sun) and sludge as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and for the calming of stressed nerves.
Touch the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets lie in the old town of Tel Aviv, the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city, the famous sea route, Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia, was linked.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with whom he lived a long and happy life.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after constellations.
Fortuna is to be the legend of all who touch the walls in the street with their constellation.
In Jaffa you can find newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries on photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusade Knights.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
These days evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Favourites for tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of the Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the journey is not taken in euros, but in dollars that can simply be changed into shekel (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed train and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations connecting the suburb to the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground cable car.
A journey within the city costs 6 Shekels regardless of the mode of transport, which is sufficient including switching for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and restaurants only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without sheds and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between various dishes with beef and veal, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls made of pure beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no straying dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this there are many well-nourished cats that stroll through the streets cozy and unhindered.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
The cats like lively places and don't say no to delicacies.
Depending on the brand, a car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, which represents an increase of 51% compared to the 2010 comparative period, before the lifting of the visa requirement on February 9, 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MEPs and citizens are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Its only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of families who remain in the home country.
On 1 December, a law entered into force requiring every migrant worker to pass a test attesting to the knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme applies only to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in retail trade.
However, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers over time according to the Federal Migration Authority.
It is not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both the receipt and the extension of work permits.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries in which Russian is the official language.
It also excludes persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problems and protection of rights
The total number of examination posts will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 relevant centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative for the introduction of the tests was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
On the other hand, before the entry into force of the law in the press, civil rights activists asked several times the following question: What does the whole thing actually mean?
What changes does the regulation require language skills both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
In particular, in response to speakers from the Migration Authority, the aim is to reduce the number of forced workers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must already be protected from their departure.
Only organized recruitment will solve the problems of foreign workers to 90%.
Migrants face problems without work, education, language skills and medical evaluation.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who will put him under the pretext of help into a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his like months without food and documents and will scour 12 to 14 hours a day.
Many complaints from our migrants reach us.
"In your home country, the One will be promised to you, and upon arrival you will be betrayed, their passports will be removed and not receive the promised wage," confirms the head of the Tajikistan Labour Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripow.
Don't yell, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they cannot only master the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: Only a few Turkmen, Usbeken and Tajikistan can afford basic education.
For there is not even money in their families to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothing, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Citizen lawyers stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only legal migrants are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, then there is no test and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of the guest workers remain illegal in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Entrance for unauthorised persons prohibited"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
Legalization also costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
You can make a fake registration quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are largely falsified and we are not registered, and then there are cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says the Tajik Umed Huschkadamow to journalists.
"Just don't spare any costs for wrong papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The falsified papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for nothing: Every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: This costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased is the agreement of both civil society and civil society.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will have time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers are offered jobs without language skills in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Interior Ministry Ignores Illegal Arms Market
The share of legal weapons in criminal offences is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten up the Arms Act for private arms owners.
This is how the authorities react to recent events: Injured at shootings at weddings and seven dead at the amok of the Moscow lawyer Dmitri Winogradow.
The police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal supported the Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be presented shortly by the Duma.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "drawing the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - call on the authorities to refrain from "sinless tightening".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very small, said the criminal attorney, Wasiliy Lesnikow, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were committed in the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private arms owners of criminals will not prevent them from operating on the black market.
At present, according to the authors in Moscow, any weapon can be found for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Supplier: from factories to officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts arms orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen both by the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez says.
On the second channel, illegal weapons are being stolen from the law enforcement agencies of criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen from both police arms chambers and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
Explosions often occurred in many military camps.
"There is evidence that in some cases it was arson to hide the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today there are countless private armament factories that do not withstand international competition and therefore throw away arms under the hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is an own, sometimes craftsmanship production as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the guns come from?
Experts calculated the proportion of each of the five channels in supplying the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was produced by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Government Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminal Literature and publicly available data on arms portals.
According to the investigators, the vast majority of illegal weapons originate from the army and the judicial authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market were there because of the "debt of those responsible for their work on weapons", says the report.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% are from thefts in the production of weapons, and 5% are from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant from a gunstore who does not want to be mentioned by name assures us that weapons found in illegal excavations have not been bought by anyone since they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for dealers to obtain the supply in a stockpiles of weapons.
A gun, such as a TT-type gun, is purchased via an enemy.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer takes the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know everything and, therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, periodically carry out control purchases by dealers offering illegal weapons," adds the sales consultant.
"Like in the luxury store"
Buyers and sellers most often find acquaintances with each other.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone became aware of me and suggested that I come to the "Begowaja" station, where a person would wait for me to bring me to a certain place, where we could then negotiate the price.
I only got the price of the gun there.
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
