Next year we would also like to be present at the Czech House in New York, and I personally, if we are already in the USA, would like to link this with appearances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have been in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organisationally?
It's not as bad as it looks at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs have to be transported in the luggage compartment. We also need to carry many instrument suitcases and other luggage.
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in each country with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
To Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than with us, we were just witnesses in Russia to the fact that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not disabled. There it is still unusual if someone is travelling in the wheelchair alone in the city centre.
