And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's still a lot of things we're gonna hang out on...
However, it should be noted that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is very common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in the public area, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to be actively involved in social events there, in which we are a bit ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly willful personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular. But if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I began to be a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in engaging in something intense.
