There are only a few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap belongs to it.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; that's only natural...
But this pity is absolutely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
It is people who can live a full life and develop if they have the means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed, this is not only a progress for themselves, but for the whole of society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you can't compromise in many things, and you have to ask for a certain discipline.
This, I believe, is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have twice a week's trial, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert trips, then the enthusiasm of many quickly disappears.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of these were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Lá­a Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't stop that.
Whoever has the will and the desire to join in is always welcome with us.
