Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the Member States of the European Space Agency (ESA) Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this Space Agency. Poland is therefore the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member on 12 November 2008 ESA).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland's way into space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish Cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, and they did not always come across understanding.
I remember here, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognized contribution to the development of space travel was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters was named after him on the earth-facing side of the moon.
Already in 1925 a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or brake the Draisine.
The information for this purpose comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered shots.
The research carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzychiegi.
From the documents submitted it is clear that the research has progressed to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, in the specialist press the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket by Ing. Rohoziński appeared, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietzna i rakietomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukovy).
The committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work, his work was finished from the start of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space travel are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the creation of a space company.
At the time, there were already the first satellite technology projects, and it was clear that the exploration of space would have a future.
As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA tried to join the International Federation for Space Navigation, founded in 1951, and, in fact, PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space Navigation.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has played a major role in the development of the highly successful Meteorological Rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first started on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 began flight tests in the Błędów desert with the two-stage RM-2 rocket.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another level of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high winds.
In 1962, however, the further development was halted.
Following the first RM rockets, the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and its starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket has a transport space of 0.4 litres capacity, Meteor-1B has 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C has 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the first flight tests began in October 1970 at the Aeronautics Institute.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which followed the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites under the Interkosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski was named after the Czech Vladimir Remek second intercosmonaut.
