In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they demanded the delivery of the overthrow of Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had kept the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the American government there was no positive way out of this situation - she could not afford to throw the shawl overboard, as this would have greatly damaged the trust of her allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent failure in the violent attempt to liberate hostages only made everything worse.
Finally, after 444 days of negotiations by the Algerian Government, the diplomats taken were released.
The fate of the hostages called for a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian moods at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the USA a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the message, six ambassadors managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, succeeded in bringing the refugees from Iran, helping them to cover up their true identity – travelling with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan, developed by the expert for "Exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Husaren piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood levels in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which are ironic and easily sharp, are therefore coming.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA centre and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the office floor, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable relaunch of his career with this film.
A smiled actor has become a respectable director, and also as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime No children's game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller city without mercy (2010).
At the same time it is Affleck's first film not playing in the local director's Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that removed the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywood.
Affleck, however, also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the entrance sequence of the destruction of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and nevertheless conveys the feeling of confusion and unforeseeableness that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck has a similar effect with his team even in fictitious scenes (the false film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that history does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
However, he works quite successfully with the little one, sometimes helping the reality a little - which then does not always work so elegantly (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is prevented by a telephone call in America, or also the persecution hunt on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its far too wide scattering, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, and so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some traction. It’s a film that can be watched with some interest and the design and retro-style reminiscent of a 70th-year-old thriller.
However, he only stirs up enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history alive to this day in a certain way and as a proof of how exaggerated the notions of the omnipotent and all-knowing secret services are, it is sufficient.
