Szabo: "Germans have to play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-European relations, Berlin is thus balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week Germany had first signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin stopped.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany has to be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without, however, being too critical of Israel.
During the Libyan uprising in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting when it was about establishing a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is precisely changing its foreign policy, away from a policy managed, as it were, by the United States, towards a German foreign policy.
Aggravatingly, Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think she was still working on her role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy as they have France or the UK.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests had an impact on the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
Firstly, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to confront the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That certainly matters.
But I wouldn't want to give too much weight to that either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German thinking.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the United States there is a great deal of understanding of the German position.
That's why I don't think this was such a dramatic break, as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even have some respect for it.
Because it signals that it is taken seriously as an international player and that its interests need to be taken into consideration.
There are different opinions on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly voted for a veto.
Are there any disagreements between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American internal policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that under Obama, the government has a fairly secret understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, represent this position publicly.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as big as they always appear.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so fond of Netanyahu's policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they can't be part of a wider line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of the relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
But I think the Germans realize that they need to play a more independent role.
Does Germany itself see itself as an important international player - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or does Germany still have a difficult leadership role?
Germany is not used to it yet, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a larger role.
For example, when we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany assumes a greater role, different anti-German feelings become free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be receptive to various neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
Now, the US's influence in European policy is steadily diminishing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else is there?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant to them and makes them much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
