Pompeii's walls adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there's the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience "to want to perform a satisfying activity but not to be able to do so".
So boredom differs from apathy, so that the person is not busy but wants to be.
In the apathy, on the other hand, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, exists in a "disturbing of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is passing only slowly".
Boredom can listen to it almost as much as depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes, although these two states may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or in the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're boring, even though we're having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - to German for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of Boredom Under the Aspect of Attention", published in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a band on which a person reads a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the nearby space that had nothing to do with the content. Others listened to it at a low volume, so it was hardly perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said that they felt more bored than the other two groups - they had problems concentrating, could not find a reason for this, and admitted their difficulties of boredom.
If one tries to focus on a difficult or strenuous task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, Associate Professor of Neuroscience at Guelph University in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if one is engaged in a monotonous activity - "like the search for defective products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored".
