So back to my question of origin: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it causes people to take on extreme physical risks and fall off gambling or drugs to alleviate them - that has shown studies.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been investigating the subject for more than two decades.
"With the boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do best.
If one is boring and one uses this energy to play and cook guitar, one becomes happy.
However, television can bring happiness in the short term, but it can escape in the long term.
So if you reach out to your bored child, you can get rid of boredom. However, it has not learned to entertain or control yourself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "self-control transfers from one situation to another".
The child not only learns to talk but also receives more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
