For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health if they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to go down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulfurous gas that flows from the earth strengthens in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphuric stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets over the wasted stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb in the turtle's tempo, keeping the balance and taking their steps carefully so that they do not slip out and fall.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 Eurocents for each kilo of sulphur they mine.
Upstairs, they pave the way between the tourists they photograph like circus monkeys and walk with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale, which has set up a mining company a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who since 1960 has been exploiting the occurrences of the volcano and (not better said) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents), because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
"As we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who normally makes three routes a day.
For each route he needs three hours, after which he is fully accomplished, but at the end of the day he has 138.000 rupees (11.5 euros).
What looks like a miserable wage for such a seemingly inhuman effort, however, is the triple of what he would earn with field labor.
"The daily wage of miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid on the day at the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not as hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, and that for a reason as important as the sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali where they are Hindus, and I brought them to Java to convert them to Islam."
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughing frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
