End of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, previously announced and to be theoretically signed by the seven rulers present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Sources at the State and Presidential Office initially announced that they would hand it over after the session, but then explained that it would be published on the Peruvian government website for a while.
On questions about the text, they stated that the content was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala.
The access of journalists to information on the summit was limited at any time.
During the day, only the picture of the president's meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulated among journalists was received by the press spokesmen of some of the governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press spokesperson.
The only document that was distributed during the day was the list of the participating presidents, which caused discomfort to the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the Presidential Office of Peru sent the media an e-mail with the "final declaration" of the summit, but this was the Humala Declaration and not the official document at the end of the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and on this occasion, the so-called so-called declaration of Lima, previously announced, was not published in spite of the press's strong call.
On the official website of the ASPA you can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed the existence of information systems for journalists, but to a large extent limited access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment by the Court of Justice of The Hague, which settles a border conflict between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would take the decision of the IGH, which begins in The Hague on Monday, in the process that Lima launched against Santiago, to listen to the pleaders of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgement on the differences we are currently presenting to this international court," said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and remains a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts," adds Piñera and greets Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
Both Presidents confirmed that they would submit to the IGH after Colombia had brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement after a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered to be a serious error, which agreed to submit to the judgments of that international court.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 since the resignation of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
Hosting President Ollanta Humala opened the discussions in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after lunch in Lima.
The head of state leaves the final document stating that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set at a total investment amount of 17 billion dollars.
On the decisions taken, he said that the countries of Unasur "will take significant steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, to which we are extending the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against insecurity in cities and against organised cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to drugs and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) should not take triumphant moves, but should serve to expand our production performance and show our peoples a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial links in South America and especially in rural and border regions... and thus unifying our countries and opening up new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a read-out statement.
Among these projects are also five Peruvians, who were located on the Querachs of his territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of whom were to ensure a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations," it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that he expected on Saturday in Mexico a meeting with his counterpart Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict respectfully following a judgment of the IGH called into question by Bogotá.
"Maybe I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," said Santos.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will deal with this matter as civilised and respectfully as possible," added Santos.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they intend to be present at the office of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc met in advance to adopt the Action Plan for 2013, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru has the presidency at the time of the regional block.
