AIDS was then synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome even with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who know nothing about their disease and in which the virus has already done damage and exhausted its immune system, and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the occurrence of the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in good time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HCG's HIV unit, who said that this information was based on a prestigious scientific publication in April of this year.
The expert on infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, the scientists concluded that although AIDS was not a death sentence, the years of survival and quality of life depended on the degree of impairment of the immune system of the individuals at the start of treatment, and that those greater chances that are non-drug-dependent: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
