Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The world-bummler of basketball, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, was connected to basket sports for more than 60 years and has traveled the whole world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large spiritual collection of the history of basketball in the country as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for six years, whether as a player of lower classes, as a player of the first national league, as an agent and as head of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or as president of the basketball association.
"I spent my life putting on many hats in basketball, even several at the same time as I was President of the BSN, Chief Executive of the National Team and President of the Association in the 1990s," Reyes remembered when visiting Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and witness them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those that recall his time at the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, where he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-manager or managing director of the club.
"These were my best years that I enjoyed most, because since 1967 I was allowed to be part of eight vaqueros championships as managing director, co-manager or trainer.
It was many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincy's debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" Ortiz took over, who was a very good administrator," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a trainer and worked at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), saying, "I have a very strong and 2 m big player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended the freelance specialist Raymond Gausse, who became a citizen and was one of our best throwers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had enabled a championship for Bayamon, Gausse would take care of another one.
The Vaqueros Championship with Gausse was granted to him, but already out of a distance, because he was already at the top of the association in 1988.
At that time he preferred to enjoy his executions and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we first won against the USA at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico.
Then came the 1990 World Championship, in which we took the fourth place, which actually should have been bronze, if not that Canadian referee, who allowed us to repeat the last move for the second time, said Reyes.
Was this group of the 1990 World Championship the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as are those who won against the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is the team of the 1991 Pan-American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered the team of the USA a fight, as they did when they won against us at the World Championship Bronze.
Not only were Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not attend in 1990 because of a knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with whom we won a gold medal and which brought us great joy, was that of the 1995 pre- Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players such as "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruiter as a substitute for the locked players because of the events on the Pan American games in Mar del Plata, we won the Gold Medal against every prognosis.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was no doubt Piculín Ortiz.
His figures at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as much as Piculin.
And this, without taking into account his career in the different leagues in which he played.
Who was the best trainer in Puerto Rico?
That is a difficult question.
We had a number of good trainers like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I like Leo Arill's work.
What do you think is the best you've achieved in the Federation?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN in the early 1990s up to 17 teams in one season.
What else you got to do?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalisation of the lower categories.
That the boys in Ponce, for example, only play in their territory and only meet in the national playoffs on teams from other corners of the island.
Today the children make unnecessary travel and games.
At least I see the result of the required trainings and courses for trainers, table-officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like to listen to music, watch videos of music of my time in YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always with me.
Larry Hagman is dead.
Larry Hagman was born on 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth (Texas) and became famous worldwide with his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series "Dallas", where he played a scrupulous, creepy and manipulous businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday afternoon due to cancer complications according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved birth town of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role that he liked most," the family said.
The family of Larry and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the celebrations of the Thanksgiving Festival.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and follow-up series, was with Hagman when he died in the Dallas hospital, said her journalist Jeffrey Lane.
He made everyone who knew him happy.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life to the full," said Gray in a communication.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted that he had been drinking a lot over the years.
In 1995 a malignant tumor was detected in his liver, and he underwent a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas" Hagman became known on television as a nice guy in the years 1965 to 1970 with the Sitcom "Enchanting Jeannie" at the NBC television station.
There he played astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is put on the head when he meets an attractive "Jshinn" (played by Barbara Eden) who will live at home with him.
He was also a performer of two comedies, which were broadcast only for a short time, such as The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His cinematographic work included critically rated roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the enchanting abominable J.R. who made Hagman a superstar.
The dramatic series of the CBS television chain over the Ewing clan and other characters in its surroundings was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertisement "Who shot at J.R.?", which was supposed to create expectation for an episode full of emotions, where the figure of Hagmann was almost killed, led to an international speculation, and millions of dollars were betted in bets.
The series thus reached a record of spectators in that time.
When the answer became known in a chapter in November 1990, it was seen by an average of 41 million spectators who turned the "Dallas" into the second most viewed entertainment program since the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million spectators.
It was Kristin, the sister-in-law of J.R. (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who had shot.
J.R. had evicted her and threatened to represent her as prostitutes if she did not leave the city. But others also had reason to want to see him dead.
Hagman interpreted the role of Ewing as a corrupt, insatiable man with a charismatic smile: an insidious businessman and unfaithful husband who sought to have his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) arrested.
"I know what should be on J.R.'s gravestone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be called "Here lies the honorable citizen J.R. Ewing".
This is the only business he didn't win.
Victoria Principal, co-author of the original series, remembered Hagman on Friday as an "enormous personality on and outside the screen".
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of lovers in the world and remains in our hearts, who have been lucky enough to know and love him.
